1. 11. praemandatis aquatus] ‘searched for by a warrant for his apprehension,’ intended to reach the place of his retreat before his arrival. The word pertentandareis omitted in F acciolati, Scheller and Smith, but not in Lewis aud Short. It means, as Wunder ad l. defines it, mandare ut aliquid curetur, prius quam conjectio ipsius rei mandatae lacurn habeat. Cp. Vatinius in Cic. ep. ad fam. v 9 5 a dicitur milti tuus seruus anagnostes fugitiuus cum Vardaeis esse,· de quo tu miti nihil mandasti, ego tamen, terra murique ut conquireretur, praemandavi, Plaut. Truc. 114, 49 mater ancillas iubet, quoniam eam decimus mensis adventat prope, aliam aliorsum ire, praemandare et quaerere muru aut puellares, qui supponantur milri.
